04082nam a22006015i 9780226535418DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265354187 a10.7208/97802265354182doi  a(DE-B1597)523365  a(OCoLC)1028216968  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHT151b.B38 2019 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a307.762231 aBeauregard, Robert A., eauthor.10aCities in the Urban Age :bA Dissent /cRobert A. Beauregard. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b12 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The City -- t2. Wealth, Poverty -- t3. Destructive, Sustainable -- t4. Oligarchic, Democratic -- t5. Intolerant, Tolerant -- t6. Encountering Contradictions -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe live in a self-proclaimed Urban Age, where we celebrate the city as the source of economic prosperity, a nurturer of social and cultural diversity, and a place primed for democracy. We proclaim the city as the fertile ground from which progress will arise. Without cities, we tell ourselves, human civilization would falter and decay. In Cities in the Urban Age, Robert A. Beauregard argues that this line of thinking is not only hyperbolic-it is too celebratory by half. For Beauregard, the city is a cauldron for four haunting contradictions. First, cities are equally defined by both their wealth and their poverty. Second, cities are simultaneously environmentally destructive and yet promise sustainability. Third, cities encourage rule by political machines and oligarchies, even as they are essentially democratic and at least nominally open to all. And fourth, city life promotes tolerance among disparate groups, even as the friction among them often erupts into violence. Beauregard offers no simple solutions or proposed remedies for these contradictions; indeed, he doesn't necessarily hold that they need to be resolved, since they are generative of city life. Without these four tensions, cities wouldn't be cities. Rather, Beauregard argues that only by recognizing these ambiguities and contradictions can we even begin to understand our moral obligations, as well as the clearest paths toward equality, justice, and peace in urban settings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCities and townsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aCities and townsxPolitical aspects. 0aCities and townsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCities and townsxSocial aspects. 0aCities and towns. 0aUrban economics. 4aUS cities. 4acontradictions. 4adaily life. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2016-2019z978311063851608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226535418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226535418.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-063851-6  DG and UP eBook Package 2016-2019c2016d2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles